 style="text-align: center;">and are made on the balance of probabilities.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(ii)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Wendell Charles Nesmith has a mental illness because he has a condition that</p><p style="text-align: center;">seriously impairs (either temporarily or permanently) his mental functioning in</p><p style="text-align: center;">areas including thought which is characterised by the presence of symptoms</p><p style="text-align: center;">including serious disorders of thought form.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(ili)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Wendell Charles Nesmith does not have the decision-making capacity to consent</p><p style="text-align: center;">to the treatment, care or support because he cannot understand. the:mainChoices</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">available to himin relation to the decision; he cannot weigh up. the: consequences</p><p style="text-align: center;">of the main choices; he cannot understand how the consequences affect.Ai</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">cannot make the decision on the basis of the matters set out above.</p><p style="text-align: center;">(tv)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">aa</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Wendell Charles Nesmith refuses the treatment determined Jn:</p><p style="text-align: center;">it relation to himself</p><p style="text-align: center;">because he has expressed ambivalence about medications. and refused, to</p><p style="text-align: center;">engage with treatment from time to time.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: c