rnail address:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">This information was completed on: 11/06/2021</p><p style="text-align: center;">Name: Rajeev Ellepola</p><p style="text-align: center;">Phone:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Email:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Page 2 of 12</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">ï¿½TRIBUNAL REVIEW REPORT</p><p style="text-align: center;">Date: 11/06/2021</p><p style="text-align: center;">TO:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">ACT CIVIL & ADMINISTRATIVE TRIBUNAL</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">ACATMentalHeaith@act.gov.au</p><p style="text-align: center;">Regarding:</p><p style="text-align: center;">NAMIE: Wendell Charles Nesmith</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Gender: Male</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">DOB; 27/06/1984</p><p style="text-align: center;">******</p><p style="text-align: center;">MENTAL ILLNESS OR MENTAL DISORDER</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">The person has a mental jliness:</p><p style="text-align: center;">and/or a mental disorder:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Yes</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">CO No</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">C1 Yes</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">No</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">MENTAL ILLNESS OR MENTAL DISORDER (Use the definitions set out in the glossary at the end ofthis</p><p style="text-align: center;">form)</p><p style="text-align: center;">The person has a mental illness</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Yes</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">disorder</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">No</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">FD Yes</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">ONo</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">and/or a mental</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">For mental illness: Describe how the illness impairs the person's mental functioning, identify the areas</p><p style="text-align: center;">of functioning that are affected by the illness and identify the symptoms that characterise the illness</p><p style="text-align: center;">and/er the behavicur that may be taken to indicate the presence of one or more of the symptoms.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Mr Wendell Nesmith is a 36 year old man with a well documented history of psychotic illness. initially</p><p style="text-align: center;">diagnosed as schizophrenia in 2018. During his most recent admission {late 2020 - Jan 2021}, the</p><p style="text-align: center;">differential diagnoses included delusional disorder and schizoaffective disorder {all of which are</p><p style="text-align: center;">different types of psychotic illnesses. The author opines that Mr Nesmithâ€™s formal diagnosis is most</p><p style="text-align: center;">consistent with schizoaffective disorder.)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Mr Nesmith's schizoaffective disorder has been characterised by;</p><p style="text-align: center;">~ delusions of bizarre and religiose themes (a religion of his own creation, based on a complex and</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">unconventional - that is, not shared by the rest of the society - system of spiritual beliefs, which</p><p style="text-align: center;">provided the reason why he should be in a matrimonial relationship with a 14 year old female.</p><p style="text-align: center;">- serious disorder of streams of thoughts, indicated by marked difficulties in explaining topics such as</p><p style="text-align: center;">the religion of his own creation in any reasonably coherent or consistent manner, or when making a</p><p style="text-align: center;">choice of treatment (repeatedly contradicting himself and unable to make a choice in the end. See</p><p style="text-align: center;">further below for elaboration on offered treatment modalities and refusal.)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Page 3 of 12</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">ï¿½- serious disturbance of mood (hypopmania), indicated by a cluster of affective (mood) symptoms</p><p style="text-align: center;">including reduced need for sleep and appetite, unusually elated or irritable mood, labile affect,</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">increased rate, volume and prosody of speech, and religiose and sexualised thought content.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">For menial disorder: Identify the disorder using the definition and describe how and to what degree</p><p style="text-align: center;">the disorder affects the person</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">ASSESSMENT (Set out details of your assessment supporting your opinion.}</p><p style="text-align: center;">Current presentation: 20/05/21</p><p style="text-align: center;">[Modified from] Psychiatric review at Belconnen Mental Health Centre (BMHC} with Dr Lee.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Wendell came for a scheduled outpatient psychiatric appointment.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Initially, engaged more calmly than previously.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Denied any clinically significant affective symptoms.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Dismissive toward psychotic symptoms - however appeared possibly somewhat less preoccupied with some of</p><p style="text-align: center;">his previous delusional contents.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Wendell quickly became argumentative re. treatment plan:</p><p style="text-align: center;">- he insisted that the author would have received a letter from "Dr Levy" (a GP?)</p><p style="text-align: center;">- claimed that Dr Levy would be taking over his care {I explained that Dr Levy would need to discuss such a</p><p style="text-align: center;">matter with ACAT and Chief Psychiatrist to be a delegate, and that | had not received any correspondence of</p><p style="text-align: center;">such at this stage.)</p><p style="text-align: center;">Wendell stated he did not have any mental illness.</p><p style="text-align: center;">tasked him what he would do with his treatment if there was to be no PTO.</p><p style="text-align: center;">At this point, as usual, Wendell became rather loud and difficult to interrupt,</p><p style="text-align: center;">"why are you forcing this {treatment) when | don't need to!"</p><p style="text-align: center;">| attempted to explain again re. possible alternative treatment options</p><p style="text-align: center;">Wendell superficially saying "yes, yes, do it, | told you", however unable to come to any agreement - as he had</p><p style="text-align: center;">been for the past many months.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Wendell stated that he would like to be on an oral medication</p><p style="text-align: center;">- |agreed with the trial of oral medication treatment with either of the conditions of 1. daily medication</p><p style="text-align: center;">supervision in place with NDIS [addit - an alternative option of a local 7-day pharmacy if Wendell could make</p><p style="text-align: center;">Page 4 of 12</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">ï¿½an agreement with the pharmacy and is happy to travel everyday to the pharmacy for this purpose], or 2. with</p><p style="text-align: center;">- regular medication serum level measure (explained that this blood test would likely be less frequent than every</p><p style="text-align: center;">2 weeks, which is the cycle of his current depot injection)</p><p style="text-align: center;">- However Wendell angrily declined either of the conditions.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">*Alternatively, | affered paliperidaone which was available crally (with supervision in community as outlined</p><p style="text-align: center;">above) or as a depot. Explained the process of trying paliperidone tablet first to establish tolerance/rule out</p><p style="text-align: center;">allergy, followed by Day 1 & Day 8 injections, followed by monthly depot for 4 months. (Invega Trinza</p><p style="text-align: center;">protocol) lf responds well, even 3-monthly depot could be considered thereafter (depending on clinical</p><p style="text-align: center;">response} - however again, Wendell, could not agree at all,</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">! explained that he could net continue to demand receiving olanzapine depat fortnightly at our clinic as he had</p><p style="text-align: center;">been, as olanzapine depot has 2-hours post-injection monitoring protocol for his own safety {risk of critical</p><p style="text-align: center;">sedation).</p><p style="text-align: center;">- usual community clinics like ours do not have such a facility or staff available. Hence there are separate</p><p style="text-align: center;">olanzapine depot clinics set up for this purpose (the nearest being University Canberra Hospital olanzapine</p><p style="text-align: center;">depot clinic which had been offered numerous times)</p><p style="text-align: center;">- Even if olanzapine depot can be given here (Belconnen Community Health Centre}, Wendell had been</p><p style="text-align: center;">frequently declining to remain in a non-abusive manner toward our stafffor the 2-hour physical observation.</p><p style="text-align: center;">That is, receiving an injection then making hostile and derogatory comments in a repeated and loud manner</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">while other patients and visitors are in vicinity. (Risk to staff and general public.) This would not be counted as</p><p style="text-align: center;">"adhering to the terms of treatmentâ€ and the health service has zero tolerance policy on any forms of abuse.</p><p style="text-align: center;">- again, Wendell vehemently declined any of the options and demanded back, "I'll just get my (current</p><p style="text-align: center;">olanzapine) injection here" after discussion of all above.</p><p style="text-align: center;">! clearly informed him again today, that he was presently and had been disagreeing with any reasonable</p><p style="text-align: center;">options of treatment offered to him (despite what he claimed, "No, tâ€™m not! You are giving me no choice!"). |</p><p style="text-align: center;">informed him the process of contravention of PTO (verbal warning that he was not adhering to the</p><p style="text-align: center;">recommended treatment) and the aim of such</p><p style="text-align: center;">- change to a safer form of treatment (*The bold part above re. alternative treatment on paliperidone} after</p><p style="text-align: center;">many months of trying to accommodate his preferences and being unable to come to a reasonable agreement.</p><p style="text-align: center;">No olanzapine depot given today, and Wendell was escorted out of the building (continued to make demands</p><p style="text-align: center;">in a loud manner which could not be delivered), but without Code Biack.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Suggestion:</p><p style="text-align: center;">As per previous multi-disciplinary team discussion - Commence contravention of PTO. Discussed with the team</p><p style="text-align: center;">leader.</p><p style="text-align: center;">1. if Wendell could try oral tablet of paliperidene in community & agreeable to our check up on the day and the</p><p style="text-align: center;">following day, | think this would be the best way for Wendell. (Offer of the least restrictive option}</p><p style="text-align: center;">2. Above to be followed by patiperidone depot commencement</p><p style="text-align: center;">3. Iffails to adhere to either of the above, a short involuntary admission in hopes of oral testing of paliperidane</p><p style="text-align: center;">and commencement of paliperidone depot.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">e</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Pate of most recent assessment</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">20/05/21</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Page 5 of 12</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">ï¿½Mental State Examination including dates conducted:</p><p style="text-align: center;">Rajeev Ellepola (CM) 26/05/21 at BMHC.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Client attended BMHC with his carer from CAHMA. Client attended BMHC for his first dose of Paliperidone</p><p style="text-align: center;">150mg IMI. Medication administered into 1) deltoid area. Nil issues during administration. Client</p><p style="text-align: center;">is due for next</p><p style="text-align: center;">depat in & days time 03/06/21.</p><p style="text-align: center;">MSE: Client attended clinic for his depot medication. Client dressed appropriately and appeared to be attending</p><p style="text-align: center;">to his activities of daily living. Client reactive in mood and affect and smiling at times. Client did not mention</p><p style="text-align: center;">any thoughts of harm. Speaking in a, â€˜regularâ€™ rate and tone and maintaining eye contact. Nil perceptual</p><p style="text-align: center;">disturbances voiced. Client did voice his apposition to continued IMI injections and stated they were "against</p><p style="text-align: center;">his religion". Client stated nil issues post oral Paliperidone, last 2 days. Client states he would like to switch to</p><p style="text-align: center;">oral medications or a three monthly depot.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Plan: For depot in 8 days time 03/06/21.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Adit: Author called client at 1500hrs to check on client post depot. First dase of IMI Paliperidone administered.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Client stated nil issues post administration of depot medication.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Rajeev Ellepola (CM) 24/05/21 at BMHC</p><p style="text-align: center;">Client attended BMHC for first dose of Paliperidone 3mg tablet. Client's Canberra Alliance for Harm</p><p style="text-align: center;">minimisation and advocacy (CAHMA) case manager was also in attendance. Client stated he was agreeable ta</p><p style="text-align: center;">taking the tablet, however continued to state he was not agreeable to having {Mi medication. Author tried to</p><p style="text-align: center;">state the benefits of the Paliperidone injection vs Olanzapine injection, however client stated he did not need</p><p style="text-align: center;">any needles, as they were against his religion.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Client was also requesting a second opinion on his current treatment. Author spoke to Dr Lee, client's current</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">psychiatrist, and a second opinion will be facilitated. Client stated, â€˜Both Dr Lee and myself donâ€™t get along and</p><p style="text-align: center;">f want a second opinionâ€™. Client also stated, â€˜I would like to work with Dr Lee, but our personalities don't match,</p><p style="text-align: center;">I think | stuffed up too'.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Client to attend tomorrow for second oral dose of Paliperidone.</p><p style="text-align: center;">MISE: Client reactive in mood and affect on engagement. Client while irritable when speaking, maintained eye</p><p style="text-align: center;">contact. Nil thoughts of harm voiced to self or others. Nil perceptual disturbances. Client irritable about</p><p style="text-align: center;">continued need for IMI injections. Client dfessed appropriately and appeared to be attending to activities of</p><p style="text-align: center;">daily living.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Sehaj Kaur (Nurse) 06/05/21 at BMHC</p><p style="text-align: center;">Wendell presented to BCHC for his depot. Author prepared depot in presence of Iqbal khalidi (social worker).</p><p style="text-align: center;">Wendell spoke about government violating his rights and BMHT violating his rights by continuing to give depot</p><p style="text-align: center;">against his wishes, Author was able to de-escalate him by providing validation and support. As author was</p><p style="text-align: center;">Page 6 of 12</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">ï¿½about to administer he continued to say "I don't like the injection...let alone the females giving it to</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">-. me...females ass f**k me...". Author asked him again if he feels comfortable with author administering the</p><p style="text-align: center;">depot, author being female clinician rechecked to gain the consent, Wendell stated "...veah you alright..." and</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">provided verbal consent.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Approx at 1150hrs, author administered 300mg olazapine into client's R) dorsogiuteal as per his request, nil</p><p style="text-align: center;">issues, Obs attended, nil issues:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">BP- 108/71</p><p style="text-align: center;">SpO2%- 97</p><p style="text-align: center;">HR- 58</p><p style="text-align: center;">RR- 18</p><p style="text-align: center;">Temp- 36.8</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">He engaged well with author, spoke about philosophy and his travelling around Australia. He showed author a</p><p style="text-align: center;">song he recorded about his "fiancee (Wendy)" {*N.B. this person is a minor, 14 years of age) who lives in</p><p style="text-align: center;">England. He spoke about his future plans with her. He was pleasant and polite. At times he complained about</p><p style="text-align: center;">health system and his wishes not being heard. Author advised him to present his wishes upon his next ACAT</p><p style="text-align: center;">hearing, he was agreeable.</p><p style="text-align: center;">MISE:</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">36 yr old male with shoulder length blond hair, dressed appropriately to weather. Mostly pleasant and polite,</p><p style="text-align: center;">at times his volume escalated whilst discussing his treatment plan otherwise normal speech, tone and volume.</p><p style="text-align: center;">He reported his mood as "good" affect reactive.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Denied hearing voices. Some bizarre thoughts expressed "...females ass f*** me...â€. Nil other issues raised or</p><p style="text-align: center;">reported. Denied having any thoughts of self harm or harm to others. Not seen responding to internal stimull.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Oriented to time, place and person.</p><p style="text-align: center;">He reported to eating and sleeping well.</p><p style="text-align: center;">He stated he will be attending ?food home at church today after 2:300m stated "...they give free food on</p><p style="text-align: center;">Thursdays at the church...free food for poor people...â€.</p><p style="text-align: center;">He stayed with author up until 1240hrs, author had to leave to attend other duties and Team Leader explained</p><p style="text-align: center;">to Wendell to stay obs. Wendell declined and stated "...1 told you i am not going te sit here alone...". Staff gave</p><p style="text-align: center;">alternative options such as magazines, working on his book etc, Wendell refused and left.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Later on staff called Wendell for welfare check and informed him to complete obs.</p><p style="text-align: center;">As per staff, Wendell came back and attended his 2-hrs obs.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Relevant past history:</p><p style="text-align: center;">index presentation in 2012 (ACT Mental Health Services}. History of admissions to mental health</p><p style="text-align: center;">hospitals in different states (VIC, NSW). In 2013 Mr Nesmith required surgery after inserting a wire into</p><p style="text-align: center;">his penis. Mr Nesmith lived in a tent on Mount Ainslie for a period of time. Managed on a PTO (ACT} in</p><p style="text-align: center;">the year 2018 and a further extension was not granted in early 2019 as Mr Nesmith was thought to be</p><p style="text-align: center;">engaging with community mental health services.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Page 7 of 12</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">ï¿½DECISION-MAKING CAPACITY</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">e</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">[oes the person, or can the person (with assistance if needed):</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(a) Understand when a decision about treatment, care or support needs to be made?</p><p style="text-align: center;">Yes</p><p style="text-align: center;">CT] No</p><p style="text-align: center;">(b} Understand the facts that relate to the decision?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">TC Yes</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">No</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">{c) Understand the main choices?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Yes</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">No</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(d) Weigh up the consequences of the main choices?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">1 Yes</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">No</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">{e) Understand how the consequences affect the person?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">CI Yes</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">No</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">{f} On the basis of (a)-(e} make the decision?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(1 Yes</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">No</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">{g} Communicate the decision in whatever way the person can?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Yes</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">No</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Describe and explain your overall assessment referring to the factors above and to the principles of</p><p style="text-align: center;">decision-making capacity set out in section & (see Glossary):</p><p style="text-align: center;">Mr Nesmith understands that he is presently subjected to PTO and a decision about his treatment is required</p><p style="text-align: center;">under PTO. Mr Nesmith denies facts related to the his symptoms/behaviour, treatment, and rights and</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">responsibilities in relation to PTO. He appears to struggle to understand what the main choices of treatment</p><p style="text-align: center;">offered to him are, hence repeatedly demanding treatment option that are noi feasible (such as demanding to</p><p style="text-align: center;">receive depot olanzapine at a wrong clinic and declining post-injection monitoring which is a part of the very</p><p style="text-align: center;">depot treatment). During the process of discussion of treatment, there is minimal evidence suggesting that Mr</p><p style="text-align: center;">Nesmith is weighing up the consequences of different treatment choices. On the basis of these factors, Mr</p><p style="text-align: center;">Nesmith does not presently appear to have a decision-making capacity over his psychiatric treatment.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Mr Nesmith often struggles to convey his treatment preferences in a consistent manner (often contradictory),</p><p style="text-align: center;">however is able to express his decisions verbally.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">REFUSAL</p><p style="text-align: center;">Â¢</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Does the person refuse to receive treatment, care or support; or, if the person has decision-making</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">capacity, refuse to consent to treatment, care or support?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Yes</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Ci No</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">If yes, describe what the person does and/or says that constitutes refusal</p><p style="text-align: center;">Mr Nesmith was discharged from The Canberra Hospital on PTO to the care of Belconnen Community</p><p style="text-align: center;">Recovery Service on 15/1/21. One of his main modes of treatment on discharge under PTO was</p><p style="text-align: center;">olanzapine depot. Below is the history of refusal since.</p><p style="text-align: center;">25/1/21 - Contravention of PTO served, as Mr Nesmith refused to receive his depot olanzapine due.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Subsequently Mr Nesmith received the depot on the same day, however refused to follow through</p><p style="text-align: center;">with post-injection monitoring, leaving Mr Nesmith at the risk of not being able to be monitored for</p><p style="text-align: center;">critical sedation post-injection. Riskman had to be lodged.</p><p style="text-align: center;">27/1/21 - Did not attend psychiatric review with the author. (Written appointment letter with time</p><p style="text-align: center;">sent on 22/1/21.)</p><p style="text-align: center;">8/2/21 - Received depot again at a wrong clinic (due to his Mr Nesmith's refusal to attend the</p><p style="text-align: center;">Page 8 of 12</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">ï¿½designated olanzapine depot clinic}. Irritable and loud in presence of public, arguing about depot at</p><p style="text-align: center;">length. In the end, received the depot, but left before post-injection monitoring.</p><p style="text-align: center;">(*From this point onward, the author will not repeat that Mr Nesmith refused to attend the</p><p style="text-align: center;">designated olanzapine depot clinic. He has never attended olanzapine depot clinic as per requested,</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">and received the fortnightly injection with the help of nurses at Belconnen Community Health Centre</p><p style="text-align: center;">where there is no staffing or clinical area for post-injection monitoring.)</p><p style="text-align: center;">6/5/21 - Did not stay for post-injection monitoring</p><p style="text-align: center;">21/5/21 - Another contravention of PTO served following the author's review on 20/5/21 (attached</p><p style="text-align: center;">above}. This was following the failure for the past three months for Mr Nesmith ta choose one of the</p><p style="text-align: center;">safe methods of treatment which had been offered to him. The choices were;</p><p style="text-align: center;">1} olanzapine depot at a designated clinic and following through with post-injection monitoring each</p><p style="text-align: center;">time</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">2) olanzapine (and valproate) oral treatment with a method of daily medication supervision (such as</p><p style="text-align: center;">NDIS medication supervision) or regular serum level measure (blood test)</p><p style="text-align: center;">3} an alternative antipsychotic trial, either as a depot which can be administered at Belconnon</p><p style="text-align: center;">Community Health Centre setting, or as an oral treatment with a method of supervision or blood test</p><p style="text-align: center;">to check the level.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Following three months of Mr Nesmith declining all three options, the last option of an alternative</p><p style="text-align: center;">antipsychotic trial was decided by the author as the delegate of the Chief Psychiatrist. Mr Nesmith is</p><p style="text-align: center;">currently undergoing a trial of paliperidone depot in community, in hopes that this may nave a</p><p style="text-align: center;">sufficient clinical efficacy.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">RISK OR DETERIORATION</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">@</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">isthe person doing, or likely to do serious harm to themself</p><p style="text-align: center;">or someone else because of the mental illness</p><p style="text-align: center;">or menial disorder?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Yes</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">CI No</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">If yes, explain your reasons jor this opinion.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Considering the facts that 1. Mr Nesmith does not believe he has a mental illness; and 2. history of</p><p style="text-align: center;">relapses in context of non-adherence to the recommended treatment, it is plausible that Mr Nesmith</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">is at risk of portraying some of the previous behaviour driven by his mental illness. Such behaviour</p><p style="text-align: center;">would include;</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">- Being involunatarily hospitalised in December 2020, after complaints were made to the AFP regarding</p><p style="text-align: center;">the conient of some of his YouTube videos. It was alleged there were references to sexual content</p><p style="text-align: center;">involving minors and indoctrinating young girls to a cult,</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">- Mr Nesmith has on repeated occasions portrayed hostility and inability ta contain his anger in a</p><p style="text-align: center;">reasonable manner in presence of general public over the past five months of community treatment.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Page 9 of 12</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">ï¿½He had to be reminded on several occasions that there were vulnerable people including children in</p><p style="text-align: center;">the vicinity, and that we would need to call security to escort him to leave if he was to continue to be</p><p style="text-align: center;">loud and abusive in public spaces such as corridors.</p><p style="text-align: center;">- In 2013 Mr Nesmith required surgery after inserting a wire into his penis. Mr Nesmith also lived ina</p><p style="text-align: center;">tent on Mount Ainslie - which were uncharacteristic behaviour and standard of living when compared</p><p style="text-align: center;">to Mr Nesmith was treated for his mental illness.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">is the person suffering, or likely to suffer serious mental or physical deterioration because of the</p><p style="text-align: center;">mental iHness or mental disorder?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Yes</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Ci No</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">If yes, explain your reasons for this opinion.</p><p style="text-align: center;">Considering his current mental state even on treatment (*unable to verify if his does are optimal due to his</p><p style="text-align: center;">refusal of blood test to check levels} and history of relapse in absence of treatment, it is highly likely that Mr</p><p style="text-align: center;">Nesmith will suffer from a significant mental deterioration - that is, unless an assertive means of treatment is</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">enforced.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">TREATMENT</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">e</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">What treatmeni, care or support is proposed? (If a treatment plan is prepared it may be attached to this</p><p style="text-align: center;">form)</p><p style="text-align: center;">{* Also see refusal section above.)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">1. Currently paliperidone depot + valproate oral treatment is being tried.</p><p style="text-align: center;">- 1a, regular ECG, as well as checking paliperidone and valproate serum levels would be recommended for Mr</p><p style="text-align: center;">Nesmith's own medical safety and ensuring clinical efficacy</p><p style="text-align: center;">- 1b. daily medication supervision either by NDIS or a local pharmacy (if available} may be able to substitute a</p><p style="text-align: center;">certain aspect of above treatment, however incompletely. For example, the required oral equivalent dose may</p><p style="text-align: center;">be too high to be converted into a daily oral dose (hence only safe in a depot form) and a regular serum</p><p style="text-align: center;">measure will be still recommended for his own medical safety.</p><p style="text-align: center;">2. Should above fail, an anitpsychotic +/- mood stabiliser treatment of a statistically higher efficacy would be</p><p style="text-align: center;">recommended (such as clozapine}, however these likely require a higher level of cooperation from Mr</p><p style="text-align: center;">Nesmith.</p><p style="text-align: center;">3. Regular case manager and doctor's review to examine clinical progress and make required adjustments to</p><p style="text-align: center;">treatmeni.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">4. \f Mr Nesmith would consider, a psychological therapy addressing the residual symptoms and the</p><p style="text-align: center;">psychological burden of own illness might be beneficial.</p><p style="text-align: center;">5. lf Mr Nesmith would consider, our team would like to recommend engaging in available group-based</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">activities to reduce social isolation, and to build meaningful relationships in real life and important social skills.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Page 10 of 12</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">ï¿½'. 6.17 Mr Nesmith would consider, our team would be more than happy to assist with occupational upskilling or</p><p style="text-align: center;">training in an area, to reduce the possibility of socio-economical marginalisation as an indirect impact of</p><p style="text-align: center;">mental illness. This, in turn, will improve the overall functionality of the person even in presence ofan illness,</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">and reduce the risk of suboptimal treatment due to lack of resources or financial means to continue treatment</p><p style="text-align: center;">in the future.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">2</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Why or how will treatment care or support be likely to reduce harm, or deterioration, or result in an</p><p style="text-align: center;">improvement to the person's condition?</p><p style="text-align: center;">The proposed treatment 1 & 2 above: will aim to address the underlying biological pathophysiology of</p><p style="text-align: center;">his illness</p><p style="text-align: center;">The proposed treatment 3 - 6: as per explained above.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">e</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Why can't the treatment care or support be adequately provided with less restriction of the freedom o7</p><p style="text-align: center;">choice and movement of the person?</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Presently, ongoing treatment based in community with help of PTO appears to be the least restrictive setting</p><p style="text-align: center;">of treatment, in which a safe and sufficiently efficacious treatment could take place.</p><p style="text-align: center;">The potential impact of suboptimal treatment of Mr Nesmith to the vulnerable members of public (such as</p><p style="text-align: center;">minors} does raise a question about if a more restrictive setting should be considered and has been consulted</p><p style="text-align: center;">with Forensic Mental Health arm of the service.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">OPINION/RECOMMENDATIONS</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Overall opinion</p><p style="text-align: center;">it is the author's professional opinion that Mr Nesmith should continue to receive an assertive</p><p style="text-align: center;">treatment with the help of PTO at present stage.</p><p style="text-align: center;">in regards to the six written questions sent by Mr Thomas Maling at Elringtons Lawyers acting on behalf of Mr</p><p style="text-align: center;">Nesmith on 09.06.2021 (Annex attached);</p><p style="text-align: center;">1. Please refer to <TREATMENT> section above.</p><p style="text-align: center;">2. Please refer to <REFUSAL> section above.</p><p style="text-align: center;">3. Mr Nesmith disagrees that he has an illness or that there is a need for treatment. As a pubiic mental health</p><p style="text-align: center;">team, we are dedicated to protect the right of the person to be treated when the person's decision making</p><p style="text-align: center;">capacity is compromised as a result of an illness of his brain. In general, one may view that the persan has a</p><p style="text-align: center;">more â€˜positiveâ€™ therapeutic relationship when the person is agreeable to the recommendations of the</p><p s