re based on the information before the Tribunal</p><p style="text-align: center;">and are made on the balance of probabilities.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(ii)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Wendell Charles Nesmith has a mental illness because he has a condition that</p><p style="text-align: center;">seriously impairs (either temporarily or permanently) his mental:â€œfunctioning in</p><p style="text-align: center;">areas including thought which is characterised by the presefice of symptoms</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">including serious disorders of thought form.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(ii)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">a</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">: on</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Wendell Charles Nesmith does not have the decision--making apa y</p><p style="text-align: center;">to the treatment, care or support because he cannot understand the:tr</p><p style="text-align: center;">3)</p><p style="text-align: center;">available to himin relation to the decision; he cannot weigh up%tsth â€˜consequences</p><p style="text-align: center;">of the main choices; he cannot understand how the consequences affecthimyand</p><p style="text-align: center;">he cannot make the decision on the basis of the matters set out above.â€</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">ï¿½ï¿½(iv)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Wendell Charles Nesmith refuses the treatment determined in relation to himself</p><p style="text-align: center;">because he has expressed ambivalence about medication.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(v)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">The Tribunal believes on reasonable grounds that because of his mental illness,</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Wendell Charles Nesmith is likely to do serious harm to himself as a result of</p><p style="text-align: center;">misadventure.</p><p style="text-align: center;">(vi)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">The Tribunal believes on reasonable grounds that because of his mental illness,</p><p style="text-align: center;">Wendell Charles Nesmith is likely to suffer serious deterioration of his mental</p><p style="text-align: center;">staie and functioning.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">(vil) The Tribunal is satisfied that psychiatric treatment, care or support is likely to</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">reduce the harm or deterioration mentioned above and is</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">likely to result in an</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">improvement in Wendell Charles Nesmith's psychiatric condition.</p><p style="text-align: center;">(viii) The Tribunal is satisfied that the treatment, care or support to be provided under</p><p style="text-align: center;">the psychiatric treatment order cannot be adequately provided in another way that</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">would involve less restriction of Wendell Charles Nesmith's freedom of choice</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">_-and movement.</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">Acting Presidential Member R Orr</p><p style="text-align: center;"><br /></p><p style="text-align: center;">ï¿½ï¿½ACT CIVIL AND ADMINISTRATIVE TRIBUNAL</p><p style="text-align: center;">Our Ref:</p><p style="text-ali