pan style="background-color: #fcff01;"><span style="font-size: large;">I wanted to thank you all for your support during these trying times.</span></span></div><div style="color: red; font-weight: bold; text-align: center;"><span style="background-color: black;"><span style="font-size: large;"><br /></span></span></div><div style="font-weight: bold; text-align: center;"><span style="background-color: black; color: #04ff00; font-size: large;">I will be publishing a new book composed of all of the letters and information that these evil people have shared with me. After this is done and I have collected all of these papers and the situation is resolved, that is when this book will go live. I have already done this with the last case, Psychiatry 101. So this is the sequel to that book which you can find here: https://books.google.com.au/books?id=FJDHDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false</span></div><div style="font-weight: bold; text-align: center;"><span style="background-color: black; color: #04ff00; font-size: large;"><br /></span></div><div style="font-weight: bold; text-align: center;"><span style="background-color: black; color: #04ff00; font-size: large;">Is it appropriate to tell these evil people that their choices will be documented publicly for prosperity's sake? I think they need to know that their decisions will be recorded in history for all of time.</span></div><div style="font-weight: bold; text-align: center;"><span style="background-color: black; color: #04ff00; font-size: large;"><br /></span></div><div style="font-weight: bold; text-align: center;"><span style="background-color: black; color: #04ff00; font-size: large;">I am a public person. My entire life is on the Internet. This is NOT a private matter. This is a public matter and their actions will be painted all over the Internet for the rest of time. I find it very sad how no one takes accountability for their malicious actions in this world. "Doctors" get away with the worst of crimes in today's society.</span></div><div style="font-weight: bold; text-align: center;"><span style="background-color: black; color: #04ff00; font-size: large;"><br /></span></div><div style="font-weight: bold; text-align: center;"><span style="background-color: black; color: #04ff00; font-size: large;">With Love,</span></div><div style="font-weight: bold; text-align: center;"><span style="background-color: black; color: #04ff00; font-size: large;"><br /></span></div><div style="font-weight: bold; text-align: center;"><span style="background-color: black; color: #04ff00; font-size: large;">Wendell<br /><br />NO REPLY</span></div><div style="text-align: center;"><span style="color: #04ff00; font-size: large; font-weight: bold;"><span style="background-color: black;">ALWAYS THE SAME FUCKING THING...<br /></span></span><h2><span style="font-size: x-large;"><span style="background-color: black; font-variant-alternates: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; font-variant-emoji: normal; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-position: normal; vertical-align: baseline;"><span style="color: red;"><span style="font-family: Google Sans Text;"><span style="white-space-collapse: preserve;">DOLOPHONOS<br /></span></span></span></span><span style="background-color: black; font-variant-alternates: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; font-variant-emoji: normal; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-position: normal; vertical-align: baseline;"><span style="color: red;"><span style="font-family: Google Sans Text;"><span style="white-space-collapse: preserve;">PHONOI
</span></span></span></span></span></h2><h2><span style="color: red; font-size: x-large;"><span face=""Google Sans", Arial, sans-serif" style="background-color: black; font-weight: 400; text-align: start;">Â Î¦ÏŒÎ½Î¿Î¹Â <br /><br /><br /></span></span></h2><div><span style="color: red; font-size: x-large;"><span face=""Google Sans", Arial, sans-serif" style="background-color: black; font-weight: 400; text-align: start;"><br /></span></span></div><h2 style="text-align: center;"><span face="Google Sans, Arial, sans-serif" style="font-size: large;"><span style="background-color: black; font-weight: 400;"><span style="color: #fcff01;">In Ancient Greek mythology, the </span><span style="color: red;">Phonoi (Î¦ÏŒÎ½Î¿Î¹)</span><span style="color: #fcff01;"> are the personified spirits (daimones) of </span><span style="color: red;">murder</span><span style="color: #fcff01;">, </span><span style="color: red;">killing</span><span style="color: #fcff01;">, and </span><span style="color: red;">slaughter</span><span style="color: #fcff01;">. While they are the literal plural of </span><span style="color: red;">phonos </span><span style="color: #fcff01;">(</span><span style="color: red;">murder</span><span style="color: #fcff01;">), they represent the concept on a </span><span style="color: red;">systemic </span><span style="color: #fcff01;">and </span><span style="color: #04ff00;">spiritual </span><span style="color: #fcff01;">level.Â </span></span></span></h2><h2><span style="background-color: black; font-variant-alternates: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; font-variant-emoji: normal; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-position: normal; font-weight: 400; vertical-align: baseline;"><span face="Google Sans, Arial, sans-serif" style="color: #fcff01; font-size: large;"></span></span></h2><h2 style="text-align: center;"><span face="Google Sans, Arial, sans-serif" style="color: #fcff01; font-size: large;"><span style="background-color: black; font-weight: 400;">Mythological Origins</span></span></h2><h2 style="text-align: center;"><span face="Google Sans, Arial, sans-serif" style="font-size: large;"><span style="background-color: black; font-weight: 400;"><span style="color: #fcff01;">Parentage: The </span><span style="color: red;">Phonoi </span><span style="color: #fcff01;">are the offspring of Eris (</span><span style="color: red;">Strife</span><span style="color: #fcff01;">).</span></span></span></h2><h2 style="text-align: center;"><span face="Google Sans, Arial, sans-serif" style="font-size: large;"><span style="background-color: black; font-weight: 400;"><span style="color: #fcff01;">Siblings: They belong to a dark pantheon of personified woes, including </span><span style="color: red;">Androktasiai </span><span style="color: #fcff01;">(</span><span style="color: red;">Slaughters</span><span style="color: #fcff01;">), </span><span style="color: red;">Hysminai</span><span style="color: #fcff01;"> (</span><span style="color: red;">Combats</span><span style="color: #fcff01;">), </span><span style="color: red;">Makhai </span><span style="color: #fcff01;">(</span><span style="color: red;">Battles</span><span style="color: #fcff01;">), and </span><span style="color: red;">Lete </span><span style="color: #fcff01;">(</span><span style="color: red;">Forgetfulness</span><span style="color: #fcff01;">).</span></span></span></h2><h2 style="text-align: center;"><span face="Google Sans, Arial, sans-serif" style="font-size: large;"><span style="background-color: black; font-weight: 400;"><span style="color: #fcff01;">Function: They represent </span><span style="color: red;">murders </span><span style="color: #fcff01;">that occur outside the battlefieldâ€”such as </span><span style="color: red;">assassinations</span><span style="color: #fcff01;">, </span><span style="color: red;">domestic murders</span><span style="color: #fcff01;">, or </span><span style="color: red;">systemic purges</span><span style="color: #fcff01;">. Their sisters, the </span><span style="color: red;">Androktasiai</span><span style="color: #fcff01;">, presided over the </span><span style="color: red;">mass slaughter</span><span style="color: #fcff01;"> of </span><span style="color: red;">war</span><span style="color: #fcff01;">.Â </span></span></span></h2><h2 style="text-align: center;"><span face="Google Sans, Arial, sans-serif" style="font-size: large;"><span style="background-color: black; font-weight: 400;"><span style="color: red;">Phonoi </span><span style="color: #fcff01;">vs. </span><span style="color: red;">Dolophonos</span></span></span></h2><h2 style="text-align: center;"><span face="Google Sans, Arial, sans-serif" style="color: #fcff01; font-size: large;"><span style="background-color: black; font-weight: 400;">The relationship between these terms highlights the difference between an individual act and a systemic state:</span></span></h2><h2 style="text-align: center;"><span face="Google Sans, Arial, sans-serif" style="font-size: large;"><span style="background-color: black; font-weight: 400;"><span style="color: red;">Dolophonos </span><span style="color: #fcff01;">(Individual): A </span><span style="color: red;">specific person</span><span style="color: #fcff01;"> who </span><span style="color: red;">kills </span><span style="color: #fcff01;">through </span><span style="color: red;">trickery </span><span style="color: #fcff01;">or </span><span style="color: red;">ambush</span><span style="color: #fcff01;">.</span></span></span></h2><h2 style="text-align: center;"><span face="Google Sans, Arial, sans-serif" style="font-size: large;"><span style="background-color: black; font-weight: 400;"><span style="color: red;">Phonoi </span><span style="color: #fcff01;">(Systemic/Collective): The overarching spirits or the "</span><span style="color: #04ff00;">atmosphere</span><span style="color: #fcff01;">" of </span><span style="color: red;">murder </span><span style="color: #fcff01;">that </span><span style="color: red;">infects </span><span style="color: #fcff01;">a </span><span style="color: #04ff00;">society </span><span style="color: #fcff01;">or a </span><span style="color: #04ff00;">lineage</span><span style="color: #fcff01;">. In tragedy, Aeschylus refers to a "</span><span style="color: red;">Phonos</span><span style="color: #fcff01;">" that breeds within a house, turning a single act of </span><span style="color: red;">treachery </span><span style="color: #fcff01;">into a cycle of systemic family </span><span style="color: red;">violence</span><span style="color: #fcff01;">.Â </span></span></span></h2><h2 style="text-align: center;"><span face="Google Sans, Arial, sans-serif" style="color: #fcff01; font-size: large;"><span style="background-color: black; font-weight: 400;">Systemic Context</span></span></h2><h2><span face="Google Sans, Arial, sans-serif" style="color: #fcff01; font-size: large;"><span style="background-color: black; font-weight: 400; text-align: start;"></span></span></h2><h2 style="text-align: center;"><span face="Google Sans, Arial, sans-serif"><span style="background-color: black;"><span style="color: #fcff01; font-size: x-large; font-weight: 400;">In Ancient Greek thought, the appearance of the </span><span style="color: red; font-size: x-large; font-weight: 400;">Phonoi </span><span style="color: #fcff01; font-size: x-large; font-weight: 400;">signaled a </span><span style="color: red; font-size: x-large; font-weight: 400;">breakdown </span><span style="color: #fcff01; font-size: x-large; font-weight: 400;">of the </span><span style="color: red; font-size: x-large; font-weight: 400;">social order</span><span style="color: #fcff01; font-size: x-large; font-weight: 400;">. When a city-state fell into stasis (</span><span style="color: red; font-size: x-large; font-weight: 400;">civil strife</span><span style="color: #fcff01; font-size: x-large; font-weight: 400;">), it was said to be </span><span style="color: red; font-size: x-large; font-weight: 400;">unde